        <caption>
          <p>Alignment scores of chromatin state sequences of protein-coding genes within a sex versus between sexes. We perform the two-sample one-sided Wilcoxon test between within-sex alignment scores and between-sex scores to quantify their differences: (<bold>A</bold>) Manhattan plot of <italic>P</italic>-values of the test between male-vs-male and male-vs-female alignment scores for all the protein-coding genes. (<bold>B</bold>) Manhattan plot of <italic>P</italic>-values of the test between female-vs-female and male-vs-female alignment scores for all the protein-coding genes. In the two comparisons, within-sex and between-sex alignment scores differ most significantly for genes on the X chromosome.</p>
